Great Plains: America's Lingering Wild

History, Nature Documentary hosted by Michael Forsberg, published by PBS in 2013 - English narration


Information
------------------------------

Follow nature photographer Michael Forsberg as he examines the remaining &quot;wildness&quot; in the Great Plains of North America. Featuring stunning imagery, the program is based on Forsberg's book of the same name. Less than 200 years ago, the Great Plains was one of the greatest grassland ecosystems on Earth, stretching nearly a million square miles down the heart of the continent. The prairie was a place of constant motion, shaped by an unforgiving cycle of the seasons. Huge numbers of bison, elk, pronghorn, deer, prairie dogs, prairie wolves and even grizzlies were common. There were massive migrations of birds and fish. But as America grew, and the land was settled and tamed, the wildness began disappearing.

